{"candidates":[{"path":"lro/lro-l-lola-3-rdr-v1/lrolol_1xxx","dataset_id":"LRO-L-LOLA-4-GDR-V1.0","title":"LRO: LUNAR ORBITER LASER ALTIMETER DATA","pds_version":"PDS3","mission":"lro","node":"geo","reasoning":"Stage 1 (GEO directory walk + label probe): this LOLA volume set contains multiple LOLA processing levels including the Gridded Data Record (GDR). LOLA gridded topography is a primary dataset you can use to characterize the setting and derive height/relief constraints around the Mare Tranquillitatis Pit area (although the pit itself is near/below LOLA’s effective spatial sampling)."},{"path":"lro/lro-l-lola-3-rdr-v1/lrolol_1xxx","dataset_id":"urn:nasa:pds:lro_lola_rdr:data_gridded","title":"Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter LOLA RDR Gridded Data Collection","pds_version":"PDS4","mission":"lro","node":"geo","reasoning":"Stage 1 (GEO directory walk + PDS4 bundle/collection inspection): PDS4 modern equivalent collection for LOLA gridded products (DEMs, derived grids) useful for regional context and elevation constraints near Mare Tranquillitatis."},{"path":"lro/lro-l-lola-3-rdr-v1/lrolol_1xxx","dataset_id":"urn:nasa:pds:lro_lola_rdr:data_calibrated","title":"Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter LOLA RDR Calibrated Data Collection","pds_version":"PDS4","mission":"lro","node":"geo","reasoning":"Stage 1: calibrated LOLA shot/track products (RDR) supporting higher-fidelity local elevation profiling around the pit location than gridded products alone."},{"path":"lro/lro-l-dlre-4-rdr-v1","dataset_id":"urn:nasa:pds:lro_diviner_calibrated:data_calibrated2","title":"Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter Diviner Calibrated Data Collection 2","pds_version":"PDS4","mission":"lro","node":"geo","reasoning":"Stage 1: Diviner calibrated radiance/temperature products for thermophysical context of the pit and surrounding mare basalts (e.g., diurnal temperature behavior often used to infer rock abundance and regolith properties near collapse features)."}],"summary":"Feature answer (context): The “Mare Tranquillitatis Pit” (often discussed as a lunar skylight/pit crater) is a steep-walled collapse hole in the basaltic plains of Mare Tranquillitatis, commonly interpreted as a possible entrance (skylight) into a subsurface void such as a lava tube.

Dimensions (widely cited, approximate; typically measured from high‑resolution LRO LROC NAC imaging/DTMs): ~100 m across (order‑of‑magnitude 10^2 m; commonly reported as ~80–120 m in diameter) and roughly ~100 m deep (tens to ~100 m).

Data to verify/measure dimensions: the GEO node does not host the LROC NAC DTM products directly, but it does host LRO LOLA topography (datasets/collections above) which provide regional elevation context. For the most precise pit diameter/depth measurements you generally use LROC NAC stereo DTMs and NAC images (discoverable via ODE product searches; e.g., an LROC NAC DTM product exists named TRANQPIT1)."}
